<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="149">
Several Asiatic species are described in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Klug" authorityYear="1845" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Chrysis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysis maculicornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculicornis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Chrysis maculicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, most of which are based on females only, with habitus and colouration similar to the common &quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mocsary" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Chrysis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysis distincta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distincta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Chrysis distincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mocsáry">Mocsary</normalizedToken>
, 1887&quot;: 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. contrasta" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="contrasta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. contrasta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tarbinsky, 2002; 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. fata" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="fata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. fata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tarbinsky, 2002; 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. kabulica" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="kabulica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. kabulica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Balthasar, 1957; 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. semenovi" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="semenovi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. semenovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Radoszkowski, 1891; 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. subdistincta" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="subdistincta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. subdistincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Linsenmaier, 1968; 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. zarudniella" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="zarudniella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. zarudniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Semenov-Tian-Shanskij, 1967. Based on the copious Central Asian specimens deposited at ZIN, we can state that the males of some of these species, closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. disticta" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="disticta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">C. disticta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are entirely blue. Nevertheless, the correct attribution of the two sexes to the same species can be considered a challenge at this stage and without direct observation of copula in the field. Moreover, specimens collected in the same collecting event in Mongolia show large variation, although genitalia are rather similar.
</paragraph>
